  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Supporting  the Tax Justice Network in Colombia</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">More progressive public agendas and elements of progressive policies around taxes and public finances are going to be developed. Progressive policy changes around taxes and public finances are going to be introduced and/or influenced by Cedetrabajo and the Tax Justice Network. Stronger alliances promoting progressive tax reforms are going to be made. Legislative power to introduce progressive policies on taxes and public finances. Redistribution through taxes will be regarded as an integral part of peace. Human rights movement become aware of the dangers of harmful privatization of public companies and oppose them. Civil society demands  that large economic groups publish information about what they pay in taxes, and so this will enhance transparency and tax justice. Tax Justice Network influences legislative reform and budgeting, so this will be more likely to see the peace accords resourced and implemented. Strengthening  the movements for demanding tax and gender justice.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Systematic follow-up to fiscal, tax and macroeconomic management of Colombian government, especially regarding their impact on the poorest sectors and women, through research and publications. Develop proposals for debates linking tax justice and the peace process in various scenarios of social mobilization, academics and in the Congress. Support citizens to monitor and denounce ineffective tax fiscal privileges to companies. Support to human rights and civil society organizations to increase their understanding and participation in advocacy initiatives on tax and fiscal justice issues. Monitoring the State&#xB4;s tax and fiscal performance through the Tax Justice Network. Provide evidence and campaign on the link between gender and tax justice.</narrative>
  </description>
